@node "News" " XtremeGames Magazine #1 - Game news "

@{bg fill}@{fg highlight}FORGOTTEN FOREVER@{fg text}@{bg background}

Charm Design has announced their new game called Forgotten Forever. It's Dune II / Command & Conquer clone with a lot of features. According to the authors, game requires AGA or CyberGraphiX, 68EC020/14, 4 MB memory and 5-10 MB HD space. Demo version wasn't available at the moment this was written, but hopefully it'll be reviewed in the next issue.

Members of Charm Design the makers of Forgotten Forever

Code: Ferenc Zavacki (zavacki@dragon.klte.hu)
Graphic: Csaba Kémeri

Visit also Forgotten Forever homepage at http://dragon.klte.hu/~zavacki.

@{"Screenshot" system "Xtreme01:Pics/VT2 Xtreme01:Pics/Forgotten.pic >NIL:"}

@{i}Kari Suvivaara@{ui}

@{bg fill}@{fg highlight}G-MEN PROJECTS@{fg text}@{bg background}

Finnish Amiga/product seller Gentle Eye is planning to release their own products. First there will be Cosmic/Mystic Planets which will be released in the early autumn. Gentle Eye's address is http://www.ge.wip.fi.

@{i}Markku Heikkinen@{ui}

@{bg fill}@{fg highlight}CLICKBOOM WANTS YOUR VOTE!@{fg text}@{bg background}

Do you think that Amiga need games like Red Alert, Monkey Island 3, Death Rally and so on? If you said yes, here is great news for you. ClickBOOM is planning to convert some of the greatest PC games for Amiga and they want your vote. You can vote your favourite games at ClickBOOM's homepage, address is http://www.clickboom.com/conversions.html.

@{i}Markku Heikkinen@{ui}

@{bg fill}@{fg highlight}SUOMI-PELI'S NEW RELEASE@{fg text}@{bg background}

We have had here in Finland few good games, like Stardust and Super Stardust. But then Amiga had financial difficulties and nearly all game companies moved to PC, but luckily there was still guys who believed Amiga still exist. Suomi-Peli has released their new game called Damage and it's for all who like destruction style games. The idea is simple; kill as much as possible. Try the demoversion which can be found from Damage's homepage at http://www.sci.fi/~damage. There you can find more information and ordering details.

I will get full version for FREE straight from the Damage's authors in the Abduction '97 demoparty which are been held in Oulu, Finland 6-8th of June, 1997, so I guess I review it in the next issue.

@{i}Markku Heikkinen@{ui} and @{i}Kari Suvivaara@{ui}

@{bg fill}@{fg highlight}CLICKBOOM SUPPORTS POWER UP@{fg text}@{bg background}

5 May, 1997: PXL Computers and ClickBOOM announce a cooperation with Phase 5 Digital Products on making games for the Power Amiga.

"We strongly believe that the future for the Amiga lies in the PowerPC processor. Furthermore, we believe Phase 5 is and will continue to be the Amiga hardware leader. Therefore, we have selected Power Amiga as our future platform of choice", says Alexander Petrovic, the PXL and ClickBOOM producer.

The first game produced for the boards will be Myst. For Phase 5 this is good news, because they will have at least one software product for their boards...

Following Myst, other forth coming ClickBOOM "killer games" will be fully optimized for the PowerPC chip, as well.

"We are happy to see how engaged ClickBOOM has realized all their ambitious projects in the past, and we are excited that their new projects will be targeted for the PowerUp accelerators", says Wolf Dietrich from Phase 5.

The exact timeline of ClickBOOM Power Amiga releases is still to be decided. Currently, ClickBOOM's strategy can be outlined in two steps:

1. Starting with Myst, a couple of forth coming projects will support both the 680X0 and the PowerPC chip.

2. ClickBOOM will use this transitional period to work on a first Power Amiga only "killer" game. After it's release, all the following games will be Power Amiga-only.

For more information, visit www.clickboom.com.

For more information on the Power Up boards and the project, visit www.phase5.de.

@{i}Kalle Kaitala@{ui}
