@node "Wendetta" " Reviewing Wendetta 2175 "

<============================================================================>
     @{b}Wendetta 2175@{ub}                                  By: @{"Markku Heikkinen" link "Editor4"}
<============================================================================>

   When I saw this game I thought: "Oh not again, Nemesis/Project X clone." I have seen and played so many different this kind of games that it's quite hard to imagine something that is not done yet. But as usually, I was wrong, when the game was loaded, first good thing was the nice techno style music. "Yes! Good start!", I though. :)

   Your mission is typical: Aliens are invading planet Earth and you have to fly in the space and destroy all aliens. Nothing special yet, but let's look a little bit closer what is the name of the game. Enemies, rocks and so on, can attack from every directions and background graphics are nice to watch, but nothing special in them.

   The full game will be more than 33 MB in size and contains seven levels: two conventional 2D-scenario and five 3D-fullspeed shooters. Everything in the game is rendered. Before every level is an introduction animation that tells you the story and describe the following confrontation. The demo version which is quite easy to complete can be found in Aminet and it's about 1.9 MB in size.

   If you like this kind of games, this is good thing to buy and sure you buy it, don't copy, right!?!

                       VORTEX DESIGN
                       PRICE 49,- DM
        FOR AMIGA 1200, 4000 AND CD³² WITH 6 MB RAM
				
       GOOD EXAMPLE THAT AMIGA IS ALIVE AND KICKING!
@endnode
@node "Robot" " Reviewing Robot World "

<============================================================================>
     @{b}Robot World@{ub}                                           By: @{"Ahti Komu" link "Editor2"}
<============================================================================>

   When I saw this game's readme -file in Aminet I was excited because it said: "A Nintendo's MegaMan -like game." Of course I quickly downloaded it to get good memories back. But, when I saw the intro-picture I was terrified of what I saw.

   This guy had definetely not used more than 5 minutes to draw it. And then there was this horrible music. Yikes!, I said. This is the worst crap I've ever heard in a game. Still (with pain) I decided to wait and see what will be next.

   The next screen said: "How do you like the music?" A very stupid question. "I hate it", is the answer. But also in that screen was a text: " At any time you can terminate the program by pressing ctrl-c." This is the only thing that should be taken seriously in this game.

   At the point where the intro started to reveal the stages I pressed fire button and I came in a point where I could choose a character. I chose the first one. It looked a bit like Jason (everyone MUST know a worst horror film in the world called: "Jason").

   Then I was able to choose the stage. I chose the first one. The stage begun. When I for the first time pressed the control pad to right I thought that my character was stucked to one point because of a bug, but soon I realized I was wrong. It just moved so slowly. I mean, its legs went faster than a sewer machine and it's body went slower than a snail.

   Then I pressed the pad up. It jumped so fast that I could hardly see it on it's way. When for the first time I died I really got surprised: death-sound was great! This inspirated me to kill more those stupid-looking "monsters".

   Most of the enemies didn't have animation at all. They died with an explosion which was quite good-sounding too :) But this is the only good thing in this game. Only change between this game's stages is that in some stages you go upwards and in some stages you go forward. They all look stupid. After second trying the game was finished. (I wonder why I did it.) This is really something for masokists.

   If you still want this game, you can find it from Aminet:
   ftp://ftp.wustl.edu/pub/aminet/game/action/robotwld.lha
                     (really DON'T bother)
@endnode
@node "Haktar" " Reviewing Haktar "

<============================================================================>
     @{b}Haktar@{ub}                                                By: @{"Ahti Komu" link "Editor2"}
<============================================================================>

   Exceptionally this not a review of a game. This is a review of a adventure-game making program. Or actually Haktar is not a program to make a game but an engine. It uses the file(s) you have created in your game-dir (that's the dir where the game is located).

   This dir is called "head-path". Anyway, although I have never before used a program like this I could say that this is something great! I mean, you can do so much with it. You can show ILBM pictures and view text files, run programs etc. This, if something, is professionally made.

   The language of the program is quite much similar to C. I'm not going to explain all commands to you. Strangely but still rationally the choice procedure has to write (How should I say this in English ;) from tail to head.

   For example you set a flag indicating that a chest is opened. Then you need to test if it is opened and if it is you make it possible to be closed. The procedure would be like this:

		ifflag chest open
		 [
		  do close chest
		   [
		    delflag chest open
		   ]
		 | (<- that's OR which makes something else if flag is
		    not set)
		  do open chest
		   [
		    setflag chest open
		   ]
		 ]

   So, that makes a chest. When for the first time you look at the chest, it is closed (chest open-flag is not set), but still it has to check first if the flag is set. I mean, this is totally rational, what could you test is there's no flag indicating that the chest is open.

   Now you might think that why not set a chest closed-flag. At the first time I went on that too, but if you at the beginning set a flag that indicates that the chest is closed, it gets closed every single time when this file is read and the program reads it again every time when something is made to chest. So, you open the chest, program re-reads the file and closes it again ;) Well, enough of that.

   When you are learnt to use this program you can make a LOT with it. You can show a picture at any time and even the gfx of the main screen is totally what you want (If you can draw what you want, I mean).

   In the package there is also 3 games made by coder. The first, "Alterhouse" is in German and I couldn't understand a thing of it but I saw that it was something great looking stuff. Graphics were great.

   The second, "Example" just shows how to make a simple game with it. And the third one "My Room" is a game that has no target to reach, but still is a great experience. It's a quite exact game of coder, Guido's room. There is an Amiga (You can even play with it!!), C64, chairs, etc. This really shows what you can do with this. This inspired me to make a little try out of my room. It worked fine. (Although I didn't make my Amiga in it) I was very pleased when I got it to work.

   Making a game with Haktar AND without an text editor at the same disk is really painful (Believe me). This program should be used with harddisk and couple of megabytes of memory (I prefer FAST).

   I'm now planning to make a RPG with this when I have time. The docs says that these games could be sent to him. And if you let him, he will spread them as PD. Though you can spread them yourself too but it's more cool to have it in a PD-disk of some other guy, don't you think? I'm going to do it.
@endnode
@node "SortTiles" " Reviewing SortTiles V1.00 "

<============================================================================>
     @{b}SortTiles V1.00@{ub}                                  By: @{"Kari Suvivaara" link "Editor1"}
<============================================================================>

   SortTiles V1.00 is a very simple WB game where you have to find a free place for the tile shown in the lower left corner. Then you have to place it in one of the five boxes above. Every placed tile gives you one point. There is a time limit; if clock reaches 12, a new tile will be shown. If you miss it, one bonus point (blue box at right) is lost. If there are no bonus points left, game over.

   You can increase count of bonus by collecting tiles of the same colour in one frame. There is only one bug in the game; when you resize the window, SortTiles sometimes messes up redraw. Hopefully this can be fixed by resizing window again. You get bored after a couple games to this game, because there aren't any surprises. SortTiles requires KS 2.0+, math libraries and 8-colour WB screen. Check it out and make your own judgement.

@{"Screenshot" system "Xtreme01:Pics/VT2 Xtreme01:Pics/SortTiles.pic >NIL:"}
