@node "Kari" " Editor Kari 'RedDragon' Suvivaara introducing himself "

<============================================================================>
           @{b}Editor Kari "RedDragon" Suvivaara introducing himself@{ub}
<============================================================================>

   Hi. I'm Kari Suvivaara, the editor. I live in the land of polar bears, Finland. Actually there are NO polar bears in Finland, believe me. :)  I saw daylight at the first time in Oulu, Finland 10.3.1980. I have two sisters: a big sister Merja, 21 and a little sister Minna, 12.

   I'm 173 cm short and weight is 65 kg. I have light brown hair and blue eyes. I am positive, loyal, enthusiastic and lazy. Hmmmm.... :)

   My hobbies include: IRC, computergames (surprise, surprise), watching television, listening to music and at summer badminton. IRC is very nice way to meet people. I use it to chat with my assistant editors because I don't want to use telephone. :)  IRC is actually part of my "job" I guess.

   Computergames have always been near to my heart. I play them nearly every day. I like almost all kind of games. Only simulators and text adventures aren't for me. My music taste is from the other edge to another, excluding classical music.

   I watch television nowadays quite little, only some series and movies. Badminton is the only sports I like and it's very cheap too. I am also ex-roleplayer, but my friends stopped playing regularly after elementary school and so did I.

   My ex-hobby still lives in my heart; I loved red dragons when I played rolegames. They are so powerful and evil creatures :)  That's why my IRC-nickname is RedDragon. Me, a powerful and evil, are you kidding again, Kari? :)  (Oh yes I am.)

   I'm studying now in Kastelli high school in Oulu. School year ends in a couple a days and next year I'm on 2nd grade. Isn't that just great? My favourite subject at school is geography. Subjects what I can't stand are history, religion and music. They are so boriiiiiiing.....ZZZzzzz.... :)

   My first computer was Commodore 64 and I played with it quite a long time until my friend bought Amiga 500. It was so fast and nice and I had to buy Amiga 500, too. Soon I bought 512k extra memory because most of the games required it. Later on I bought external floppy drive which broke up nearly year ago. :(

   I was getting bored to disks in 1993 and I wanted a harddrive. Unfortunately I didn't know much about harddrives that time so I bought A2000, 1+2 MB RAM, 20 MB harddisk(!) and monitor in June 1993. That 20 MB harddisk felt like superturbofloppy, but nowadays that HD is *very* slow and small.

   I bought Mannesmann Tally MT81-printer little later which is still regularly used in my A1200. I sold A500 away in 1993 to get money to that very printer. In the end of 1994 my friend bought A4000 with 68040-prosessor. Damn, it was fast! AGA graphics and MultiSync-monitor, wow! I was jealous...

   Well, A1200 was also new machine that time and I decided to buy one, but then it happened...Commodore was bankrupt and I was desperate. I even thought to sell A2000 away and buy a PC! I was wise when I didn't to it because Escom saved (?) Amiga from the sure death.

   I bought Escom's A1200 in January 1996. At last! AGA-chipset, better prosessor, faster memory, newer KS, etc. than in old A2000! Later on I noticed that 2 MB CHIP is far from enough and prosessor isn't very fast. I began to dream about accelelator and then the miracle happened: I got an award from Finnish Red Cross for my good school success!

   I bought Blizzard 1230-IV/030/50 MHz with 16 MB FAST from a good friend of mine (thank you Mikael!) who was preparing for final tests in school. This is my present situation with computers.

   I have also dreamed (also when Commodore were alive) of a very fast PC with all the spices but then I thinked again and buried the dreams because I don't like WindBlows 3.11/95 or any other GUIs on PC. PC is very suitable for Internet access but that is the only USEFUL thing you can do with them. (Hmmm...is surfing in the Internet REALLY useful?)

   I don't like GUIs which take up to 16 MB RAM (Windows...) and then programs are loaded to SLOOOOOOOOOW HDs. That's why Amiga feels so fast compared to PC because Amiga don't actually need virtual memory and at the same time those nasty *BIG* swapfiles which slow up booting dramaticly. PCs also get worthless after couple of years because new super programs require new superextrafast Pentium SUPERPRO 999 MHz, 256 MB RAM and WindBlows 2002 ;)

   Ok, that enough. If you want to write to me, here's my e-mail address: karisu@kastelli.edu.ouka.fi. See you in the future!

