   My name is Kalle Kaitala, I'm known as Cobrian in the 'Net, or at least I should be. My computerhobby began when I was about 4-5 years old. My first "computer" was a Commodore Vic-20. It was followed by a C64, a damn good machine back then. Then I got into the consolespin for a while, and I bought a Nintendo and after that a Sega MegaDrive.

   My first contact to an Amiga was at my friends home, he had a Amiga 500. I thought it was awesome. And it was. I soon got a Amiga 600, but I didn't like it that much. Then I got my machine that I have been using for a at least few years now, the Amiga CD³².

   Soon I began to think about expanding the machine. I ordered an SX-1 expansion module from England. Then I got a PC AT-101 keyboard, which is compatible with the SX-1 keyboard socket. I also got a floppy drive and a little later a hard drive. Then I noticed that I was always running out of memory. I got an 8 MB SIMM. That was about 9 months ago. Then then the machine started to crash with no *obvious* reason. I found out that it was a problem with the voltage feed in the SX-1. An Amiga-shop began to try to fix it (Thanks to Garry Cardinal), but my machine isn't fixed yet...It's still has the same problem (because it's not fixed ;).

   I'm at ninth class in school (after summer holiday of course), a normal student like anyone else. I like technomusic, good games and animations, snowboarding and watching Chinese (Manga) cartoons...

